'''Takei Ōtomonushi no Kami''' (武居大伴主神, historical kana: たけゐおほともぬしのかみ) is a {{ill|Kami|ja|神 (神道)|12=draft|12=draft}} associated with local folklore and the {{ill|Suwa Faith|ja|諏訪信仰|12=draft|12=draft}} in the {{ill|Suwa region|ja|諏訪地方|12=draft|12=draft}} of [[Nagano Prefecture]].

== Overview ==

The deity's name is also written as '''Takei Ōtomo no Kami''', '''Takei Ebisu''', or '''Takei Emishi'''. Additionally, the 'Suwa Shimosha Daihōri Takei Kei Diagram' identifies "Takei Ebisu no Kami" as a distinct deity, considered the child of Takei Ōtomo no Kami.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/1185913/45 |title=Suwa Shimosha Daihōri Takei Kei Diagram |publisher=Suwa Historical Collection |date=1938}}</ref>

Takei Ōtomonushi is regarded as one of the original deities of the Suwa region. According to legend, {{ill|Takeminakata no Kami|ja|建御名方神|12=draft|12=draft}} (Suwa Myōjin), enshrined at {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft|12=draft}}, encountered resistance from Takei Ōtomonushi and {{ill|Moreya no Kami|ja|洩矢神|12=draft|12=draft}}. However, both were defeated and subsequently became vassals of Takeminakata.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/765072/29 |title=Guardian Gods and Takei Ōtomonushi |publisher=Shinano History Collection |date=1910}}</ref> Other versions suggest disputes between Moreya and Takeminakata over entering Suwa.<ref>Yamada Hajime, 'Takei Ōtomonushi as a Vassal,' Suwa Daimyōjin, 1929.</ref>

According to the traditions of {{ill|Tateshina Shrine|ja|蓼科神社|12=draft|12=draft}} in [[Tateshina, Nagano|Tateshina]], Takei Ōtomonushi surrendered his territory to Takeminakata and ascended Mount Tateshina.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tateshina Shrine|url=http://www.nagano-jinjacho.jp/shibu/03tousin/02kitasaku/2121.htm|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>

== Genealogy ==

Takei Ōtomonushi is considered the ancestor of the {{ill|Takei Horibe (Suwa Taisha)|ja|武居祝|12=draft|12=draft}} priestly lineage, which was historically managed by the {{ill|Imai Clan (Suwa)|ja|今井氏|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>Ōta Ryō, ‘Shinano,’ Isobe Kōyōdō, 1924.</ref>

== Shrines ==

[[File:蛭子社（武居会美酒） - Takei-Ebisu Shrine.jpg|thumb|<center>Ebisu Shrine (Takei Ebisu)</center>]]

* {{ill|Takei Ebisu Shrine|ja|武居恵比須社|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shimosuwa, Suwa District, Nagano Prefecture)

**Located behind the {{ill|Autumn Shrine|ja|秋宮|12=draft|12=draft}} of Suwa Taisha Shimosha. Dedicated to {{ill|Ebisu|ja|えびす|12=draft|12=draft}}.

* {{ill|Hiruko Shrine|ja|蛭子社|12=draft|12=draft}} (Takei Ebisu) (Suwa City)

**One of the subordinate shrines of Suwa Taisha Kamisha. Includes the ruins of Takei Hata and Takei Castle.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Takei Hata Ruins|url=https://suwacitymuseum.jp/nandemo/koumoku/0100/010212.htm}}</ref>

* {{ill|Ōtomo Shrine (Saku)|ja|大伴神社 (佐久市望月)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Saku City, Mochizuki)

**Traditionally linked to Takei Ōtomonushi, though evidence is speculative.<ref>‘Saku County Gazetteer,’ 1983.</ref>
== See Also ==

* {{ill|Takeminakata no Kami|ja|タケミナカタ|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Moreya no Kami|ja|洩矢神|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Mount Tateshina|ja|蓼科山|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Ebisu|ja|えびす|12=draft|12=draft}}


