Takei Ōtomonushi is regarded as one of the original deities of the Suwa region. According to legend, {{ill|Takeminakata no Kami|ja|建御名方神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeminakata no Kami|qq=}} (Suwa Myōjin), enshrined at {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Taisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa-taisha|qq=}}, encountered resistance from Takei Ōtomonushi and {{ill|Moreya no Kami|ja|洩矢神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moreya no Kami|qq=}}. However, both were defeated and subsequently became vassals of Takeminakata.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/765072/29 |title=Guardian Gods and Takei Ōtomonushi |publisher=Shinano History Collection |date=1910}}</ref> Other versions suggest disputes between Moreya and Takeminakata over entering Suwa.<ref>Yamada Hajime, 'Takei Ōtomonushi as a Vassal,' Suwa Daimyōjin, 1929.</ref>

According to the traditions of {{ill|Tateshina Shrine|ja|蓼科神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tateshina Shrine|qq=}} in [[Tateshina, Nagano|Tateshina]], Takei Ōtomonushi surrendered his territory to Takeminakata and ascended Mount Tateshina.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tateshina Shrine|url=http://www.nagano-jinjacho.jp/shibu/03tousin/02kitasaku/2121.htm|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>

== Genealogy ==

Takei Ōtomonushi is considered the ancestor of the {{ill|Takei Horibe (Suwa Taisha)|ja|武居祝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takei Horibe (Suwa Taisha)|qq=}} priestly lineage, which was historically managed by the {{ill|Imai Clan (Suwa)|ja|今井氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imai Clan (Suwa)|qq=}}.<ref>Ōta Ryō, ‘Shinano,’ Isobe Kōyōdō, 1924.</ref>

