'''Takei Ōtomonushi no Kami''' (武居大伴主神, historical kana: たけゐおほともぬしのかみ) is a {{ill|Kami|ja|神 (神道)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kami|qq=}} associated with local folklore and the {{ill|Suwa Faith|ja|諏訪信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Faith|qq=}} in the {{ill|Suwa Region|lt=Suwa Region|lt=Suwa region|ja|諏訪地方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa region|qq=}} of [[Nagano Prefecture]].

== Overview ==

The deity's name is also written as '''Takei Ōtomo no Kami''', '''Takei Ebisu''', or '''Takei Emishi'''. Additionally, the 'Suwa Shimosha Daihōri Takei Kei Diagram' identifies "Takei Ebisu no Kami" as a distinct deity, considered the child of Takei Ōtomo no Kami.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/1185913/45 |title=Suwa Shimosha Daihōri Takei Kei Diagram |publisher=Suwa Historical Collection |date=1938}}</ref>

Takei Ōtomonushi is regarded as one of the original deities of the Suwa region. According to legend, {{ill|Takeminakata|lt=Takeminakata|lt=Takeminakata no Kami|ja|建御名方神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeminakata no Kami|qq=}} (Suwa Myōjin), enshrined at {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Taisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa-taisha|qq=}}, encountered resistance from Takei Ōtomonushi and {{ill|Moriya|lt=Moriya|lt=Moreya no Kami|ja|洩矢神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moreya no Kami|qq=}}. However, both were defeated and subsequently became vassals of Takeminakata.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/765072/29 |title=Guardian Gods and Takei Ōtomonushi |publisher=Shinano History Collection |date=1910}}</ref> Other versions suggest disputes between Moreya and Takeminakata over entering Suwa.<ref>Yamada Hajime, 'Takei Ōtomonushi as a Vassal,' Suwa Daimyōjin, 1929.</ref>

According to the traditions of {{ill|Tateshina Shrine|ja|蓼科神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tateshina Shrine|qq=}} in [[Tateshina, Nagano|Tateshina]], Takei Ōtomonushi surrendered his territory to Takeminakata and ascended Mount Tateshina.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tateshina Shrine|url=http://www.nagano-jinjacho.jp/shibu/03tousin/02kitasaku/2121.htm|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>

== Genealogy ==

Takei Ōtomonushi is considered the ancestor of the {{ill|Takei Horibe (Suwa Taisha)|ja|武居祝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takei Horibe (Suwa Taisha)|qq=}} priestly lineage, which was historically managed by the {{ill|Imai Clan (Suwa)|ja|今井氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imai Clan (Suwa)|qq=}}.<ref>Ōta Ryō, ‘Shinano,’ Isobe Kōyōdō, 1924.</ref>

== Shrines ==

